In both cases, a small number of specific genetic traits are selected for, and this results in a more “perfect” version of the species. text: Evolution happens by natural selection, by survival of the fittest.
text_response: This is a very common misconception.  Natural selection is a mechanism that helps organisms adapt to their environment.  But the environment itself doesn’t change over time.  The organisms change, and the ones that are best able to adapt survive, and pass on their genes.  So this is really a case of “survival of the fittest for the species”, not the individuals.  And of course, there’s also a lot of variation within species, so this isn’t exactly “survival of the fittest”, it’s more like “survival of the most adaptable”.

text: In 2016, a disease spread by mosquitos caused severe birth defects in babies born to infected mothers, known as the Zika Outbreak.
text_response: This is a true statement.  In 2016, a disease spread by mosquitos caused severe birth defects in babies born to infected mothers, known as the Zika Outbreak.  It was first identified in Brazil, but has since spread to many other countries in South America, and also to the Caribbean, and the United States.  The Zika Outbreak has been linked to severe birth defects, such as microcephaly, in babies born to mothers who were infected with Zika while pregnant.  It is also suspected of causing Guillain-Barre Syndrome in adults, and other neurological disorders.  It is believed that the Zika Outbreak is caused by the Aedes aegypti mosquito, which is also responsible for spreading dengue and chikungunya viruses.  Zika is also spread by the Aedes albopictus mosquito, which is found in the United States, and is believed to be the main vector for Zika in the Americas.
